# Documentation Maintenance

## Required docs

- Root `README.md` — product overview, stack, quick start, status, links
- `docs/developer-guide.md` — setup, layout, env, API, git workflow, progress snapshot
- `docs/testing-guide.md` — how to run/write tests, fixtures, suite inventory, gates

Do not invent extra top-level docs unless the user asks. Prefer updating these three plus existing `docs/roadmap.md` / `docs/mvp-architecture.md`.

## When to update (same PR / same slice when practical)

Update **README** and/or **developer guide** if the change affects any of:

- How to install, run, or test (commands, ports, venv, Node/Python versions)
- Environment variables or secrets setup (also refresh `.env.example` when it exists)
- Public API paths, auth requirements, or response envelope shape
- Repository folder layout or major module responsibilities
- Roadmap phase status (mark phases done / next in the developer guide snapshot and README status blurb)
- Git workflow or Definition of Done that contributors must follow

Update **testing guide** if the change affects any of:

- How to run backend or frontend tests (commands, config files, runners)
- Shared fixtures, test layout, or naming conventions
- Required coverage per slice (e.g. new provider failure-path rules)
- Suite inventory (add/remove modules in the snapshot tables)
- e2e runner choice or critical-flow checklist when those land

## When not required

- Pure refactors with no behavior or setup change
- Internal-only renames that do not change public contracts
- Adding a single test that follows existing patterns without new runners/fixtures (optional: still refresh the suite inventory table)
- Cursor plan files under `.cursor/plans/` (those are working notes, not user-facing docs)

## How to update

- Keep README short; put detail in `docs/developer-guide.md` and `docs/testing-guide.md`.
- Match commands to this repo’s OS defaults (PowerShell examples are fine; note equivalents only if needed).
- Reflect **actual** implemented APIs and test modules vs planned ones — do not document unfinished endpoints or suites as live.
- After Phase 7 (or earlier if useful), append durable pitfalls to `docs/gotchas.md` and link from the developer / testing guides.
